===Etymology===
[[back-formation|Back-formation]] of singular form from plural {{m|en|seraphim}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|seraphim}}, from {{etyl|he|en}} {{m|he|שרפים|tr=serafim|sc=Hebr}}, plural form of {{m|he|שרף|tr=saraf|sc=Hebr}}. The plural "seraphim" occurs in the King James Bible (Isaiah chapter 6).

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈserəf/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|seraphs|seraphim|seraphims}}

# {{lb|en|biblical}} A six-winged [[angel]]; the highest [[choir]] or order of angels in Christian [[angelology]], ranked above [[cherub]]im, and below [[God]]. A detailed description can be found at the beginning of [http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Bible_%28World_English%29/Isaiah#Chapter_6 Isaiah chapter 6]

